# GitSeep: Geological History Percolation Rules
#
# History isn't just a line; it's a geological stack.
# When we commit, we add a new layer (stratum).
# Often, a change made at the surface (HEAD) actually belongs deep in a lower stratum.
# Sometimes, a change made in a lower stratum better belongs to an upper stratum commit.
#
# This file defines the "Permeability Rules":
# Mapping: Bedrock Author Date -> List of owned paths OR Dictionary with `branch` and `paths`
#
# All changes to these paths from other commits will either:
# 1. Percolate DOWN through intermediate layers to settle into an older Bedrock.
# 2. Seep UP through intermediate layers to settle into a newer Bedrock.
# 3. Sediment (Sync) into feature branches if a `branch` is specified.
# 4. Lithify (Squash) multiple historical versions into a single Bedrock record.
#
# Note: If multiple rules overlap, the most specific (longest) path always wins!
# The order of rules and the paths in this files does not matter.

# Android Studio for Platform (ASfP) Custom Image
"2026-04-14 17:36:44 +0000":
  branch: feat/android-studio-for-platform
  paths:
    - examples/images/android-studio-for-platform/

# Antigravity Custom Image
"2026-04-13 12:24:06 +0000":
